metadata.name: Unicorn #1270
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.

Twitter: @unicorn_nft_art
Web: https://unicorn-nft.web.app/

by @lucky26puch, @AgataBaranova17
Made in 2022

License: CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Tally! #6188
metadata.description:
Tally! Is a year long, free, open edition to celebrate fxhash v2. Data from the minting of Tally! will be used to create other new artworks.

This artwork is simply about counting up from one to wherever we end up, with a litle bit of Fizz Buzz thrown in. Mints that have a prime numbers* as factors will have slight variations. Sometimes those variations will combine, sometimes you have to get to really high numbers for multiple prime numbers to combine.

Where the finally Tally! ends up who knows? But there's going to be a lot of tallying along the way, and it'll give you something to do while waiting between other mints.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

'?forceWidth=xxxx' on the end of the URL to change the width of the image
's' = save image

metadata.name: Padina #107
metadata.description:
Padina collection focuses on the natural phenomenon where living organisms grow by adding layers of matter in a particular direction.
Formed shape resembles the algae genus Padina, but similarities can also be found in the world of fungi, like genus Trametes.

There are ten hand-picked color palettes, three composition types.
Multitude of variables control leaf surface details.
Each leaf consists of countless dots, which end up creating harmonic, or more chaotic patterns.


Double click: reset animation. 
Press "S" to save 4000px file. This can be slow.


Libs used: p5js, three.js

metadata.name: <iframes> #432
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #4
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Planetarium #151
metadata.description:
Francesco Forcellini, November 2022, Milano, Italy.
Compositions of spheres made with grids, proportions, symmetries and  broken symmetries,  order and casualties.


To save an image with the size of the window press S once the image is fully rendered.
To save a Hi-Resolution image 6000px x 8000px press H and wait, the page will reload and start to render.


Published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.
Built using p5js,a custom WEBGL shader and a shader with a modified version of "cnoise" by Stefan Gustavson.
See the License.md for license details.

metadata.name: CSS Molecules #231
metadata.description:
This 3d animated work is composed almost completely of HTML + CSS. There is a limited amount of javascript to construct the scene and facilitate interactive controls. 🚫 <canvas>!

A bit of history about this approach: As my first coding language HTML and CSS holds a special place in my heart. Even when I jumped into 3D my first creations were made with just some html + css coded in notepad. Earlier this year I took this idea to the next level with a yet-to-be-released 3D bedrooms project, filling it with objects and ever-refining my scene construction practice. This system for scene construction became the basis for a few other generative projects here on fxhash under my pseudonym htmlcss.tez. Here I abandon my usual representational focus with this technique and dive right into the abstract.

metadata.name: Snake Alley #136
metadata.description:
Snake Alley is a place in my neighborhood where the sidewalk is narrowly bounded by low-hanging branches on one side and a steep ditch one the other. I have seen countless snakes dart across the sidewalk there at dusk. 

I always wind up at Snake Alley, wearing sandals, at dusk.

This generative system creates unique outputs for each hash. The compositions are organized like spokes through a series of concentric rings, like the Dharmachakra, however these are twisted and centered around an out-spiraling function. Higher-torque versions look more twisted and gnarled, while low-torque versions look like rays emanating from the center.

A number of branches connect each outer ring with its adjacent, inner ring. The layers of branches fill the space with low, medium, or high density - full of circles drawn from the outer layers to the innermost layer. The circles themselves are small or large, within each output.

Fifteen color palettes named after different kinds of snakes were used to lightly color the edges, each drawn with equal likelihood. The titles and colors were adapted from different snake species, typically variants found in the southeastern US, when different colorations occur in other regions. The coral, corn, and milk snakes around Charleston have similar coloration in nature, and their similar color gradients reflect this fact.

I originally composed this artwork in the R Statistics language. I translated the system to p5.js for the one-year anniversary of fxhash. Proceeds from sales will go to Processing.org, the organization that is developing p5.js. #fxhashturnsone 

Verified NFT collectors can purchase a fine art print for their unique token at vadenart.com

About the artist: Kenny Vaden is a generative artist based in Charleston, SC. His art experience included drawing, painting, stained glass apprenticeships, and nature photography. Vaden’s code-based artworks are available online as limited edition or single edition fine art prints, as well as NFTs on Quantum.art, Flamingo DAO Flutter, OpenSea, Objkt, fxhash, and Foundation. More information about the artist and artwork is available on vadenart.com

metadata.name: Haze #5
metadata.description:
Our third project is all about testing the perlim noise function.
Inspired by different projects on fxhash, we tried to produce a randomly generated landscape with a hazed touch and played with different light scatters.
We hope you like it, enjoy.

metadata.description:
“There is no science without fancy and no art without fact.” ― Vladimir Nabokov

Dimensions are structured between lines and squares, while the colour intertwine with one another. The composition was inspired by Edwin Abbott's Flatland.

metadata.name: Galactica #7
metadata.description:
Galactica shows us the landscapes of a distant exoplanetary system made up of 10 planets.
Standing on one of these planets with its particular geomorphology, we may see faraway galaxies, natural satellites and/or another planet in the sky.

The combination of the various features can give life to up to 415,000 different versions, taking into account the differences not related to features the versions rise to about 12 billion.

Press "s" to get a 2000x2000 pixels jpg.

Generative artwork by Gandhiavelli, @gandhiavelli. Made with p5js in 2022.
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Bored in Math Class #180
metadata.description:
Bored in Math Class is a project all about exploring grids. Using grids is common in generative art, and I wanted to see how far I could push this simple technique. I integrated an irregular square packing algorithm described by Gorilla Sun on one of his blog posts to give the compositions more variety rather than just having a uniform grid. I explored a bunch of different ideas and repurposed some old code to generate patterns inside each square. Many of the patterns can be layered on top of each other to make the composition even more interesting. I decided to call it "Bored in Math Class" because it has a playful feel and the grids remind me of graph paper that I would doodle on when I was bored [in math class of course].

There are 10 color palettes, 5 different types of grids, and 8 types of patterns (though they can be layered to create more).

Press 'p' while on Live View to save a high quality (4000x4000) png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js

Licensed under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Late Night Sketches #13
metadata.description:
This project is part of an experiment combining hand-drawn "squiggles" and turning them into something unexpected. 

The assets used in this project were hand-drawn with markers, pens, brushes, and ink. I will sit down for several hours and draw a page of elements in one of my sketchbooks. I then scan the drawings and separate them into transparent png files in Photoshop. Then the p5.js sketch takes those images and places them according to a grid. 

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: print size @ 3000px x 3000px
